<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-09-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-09-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="58" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Conference files, lot 60 D 627, CF
                            375</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_EDENSA1" type="from">Eden</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d58fn1">The source text was given to <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> by British Ambassador
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MAKINSRM1">Makins</persName> during a
                                meeting at noon on Sept. 15. A memorandum of this conversation,
                                prepared by <persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName>,
                                is in Department of State file 740.5/9–1554.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-09-15">September 15,
                            1954</date>.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Foster</persName></hi>:] I received your message<note n="2" xml:id="d58fn2">This is a reference to <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName>’ letter of Sept. 14,
                                    <ref target="#pg_1192">p. 1192</ref>.</note> just as I was on
                            the point of leaving Rome. I shall be glad to see you in London on
                            whatever day would suit you. The dates September 27 and 28 which you
                            suggest for the preliminary nine power conference should, I think, prove
                            possible. We too had hoped that the <gloss target="#t_EDC1">E.D.C.</gloss> would be passed. But every country now agrees that
                            as things are there is no present possibility of reviving the
                            supranational idea. We must encourage other forms of European unity.</p>
                        <p>[Kindest regards,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Anthony</hi></persName>]</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>